</tr><tr><td style="text-align:right;font-size:115%;padding-top: 0.6em;"><div class="plainlinks hlist navbar mini"><ul><li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Hindu_scriptures" class="mw-redirect" title="Template:Hindu scriptures"><abbr title="View this template">v</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Hindu_scriptures" class="mw-redirect" title="Template talk:Hindu scriptures"><abbr title="Discuss this template">t</abbr></a></li><li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Hindu_scriptures&amp;action=edit"><abbr title="Edit this template">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><i><b>Shruti</b></i> or <i><b>Shruthi</b></i> (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit_language" class="mw-redirect" title="Sanskrit language">Sanskrit</a>: <span lang="sa">श्रुति</span>, <a href="/wiki/IAST" class="mw-redirect" title="IAST">IAST</a>: <i><i lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit transliteration">Śruti</i></i>, <small>IPA:&#160;</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/Sanskrit" title="Help:IPA/Sanskrit">[ɕɽʊtɪ]</a></span>) in Sanskrit means "that which is heard" and refers to the body of most authoritative, ancient <a href="/wiki/Religious_text" title="Religious text">religious texts</a> comprising the central canon of <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hinduism</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-jameslochtefeld_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jameslochtefeld-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It includes the four <a href="/wiki/Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedas</a> including its four types of embedded texts—the <a href="/wiki/Samhita" title="Samhita">Samhitas</a>,  the early <a href="/wiki/Upanishads" title="Upanishads">Upanishads</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Brahmanas" class="mw-redirect" title="Brahmanas">Brahmanas</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Aranyakas" class="mw-redirect" title="Aranyakas">Aranyakas</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-wendydof_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wendydof-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><i>Śruti</i>s have been variously described as a revelation through <i>anubhava</i> (direct experience),<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> or of primordial origins realized by ancient <a href="/wiki/Rishi" title="Rishi">Rishis</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-jameslochtefeld_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-jameslochtefeld-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In Hindu tradition, they have been referred to as <i>apauruṣeya</i> (not created by humans).<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The <i>Śruti</i> texts themselves assert that they were skillfully created by <a href="/wiki/Rishi" title="Rishi">Rishis</a> (sages), after inspired creativity, just as a carpenter builds a chariot.<sup id="cite_ref-scharfe_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-scharfe-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>All six <a href="/wiki/Hindu_philosophy" title="Hindu philosophy">orthodox schools of Hinduism</a> accept the authority of <i>śruti</i>,<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-elisa_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-elisa-9">&#91;note 1&#93;</a></sup> but many scholars in these schools denied that the <i>śruti</i>s are divine.<sup id="cite_ref-royperrett_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-royperrett-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> <i><a href="/wiki/%C4%80stika_and_n%C4%81stika" title="Āstika and nāstika">Nāstika</a></i> (heterodox) philosophies such as the <i><a href="/wiki/Charvaka" title="Charvaka">Cārvāka</a></i>s did not accept the authority of the <i>śruti</i>s and considered them to be flawed human works.<sup id="cite_ref-richardhayes_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-richardhayes-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-ma_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ma-13">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Shruti (<i>Śruti</i>) differs from other sources of Hindu philosophy, particularly <i><a href="/wiki/Sm%E1%B9%9Bti" class="mw-redirect" title="Smṛti">smṛti</a></i>  "which is remembered" or textual material. These works span much of the history of Hinduism, beginning with the earliest known texts and ending in the early historical period with the later Upanishads.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Of the <i>śruti</i>s, the Upanishads alone are widely known, and the central ideas of the Upanishadic <i>śruti</i>s are at the spiritual core of Hindus.<sup id="cite_ref-wendydoniger_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wendydoniger-15">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-patrickolivelle_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-patrickolivelle-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><h2 id="mw-toc-heading">Contents</h2><span class="toctogglespan"><label class="toctogglelabel" for="toctogglecheckbox"></label></span></div>
