<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=%C5%9Aruti&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-elisa-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-elisa_9-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-elisa_9-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Elisa Freschi (2012): The Vedas are not <a href="/wiki/Deontological_ethics" title="Deontological ethics">deontic</a> authorities in absolute sense and may be disobeyed, but still recognized as an deontological <a href="/wiki/Epistemology" title="Epistemology">epistemic</a> authority by a Hindu orthodox school;<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> (Note: This differentiation between epistemic and deontic authority is true for all Indian religions)</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
